1
00:02:48,751 --> 00:02:52,005
<i>Dr. Ross, we've got 
satellite from the Congo.</i>

2
00:02:53,464 --> 00:02:56,050
- What did he say, Rudy? 
- I can't repeat it here.

3
00:02:56,217 --> 00:02:58,428
- It's Charles. 
- It's Charles.

4
00:02:59,679 --> 00:03:01,764
- It won't work. 
- He changed the code?

5
00:03:01,931 --> 00:03:04,267
The old man's got me changing it 
every three hours.

6
00:03:04,434 --> 00:03:09,022
- Rudy, Rudy, Rudy, Rudy. 
- Very inventive.

7
00:03:09,814 --> 00:03:12,108
Just in time. 
We should have a visual momentarily.

8
00:03:12,275 --> 00:03:14,736
- They said they found it. 
- You're kidding.

9
00:03:14,903 --> 00:03:19,365
Seven volcanoes, and he picks the right 
one. His luck's finally changed.

10
00:03:21,075 --> 00:03:24,370
- Karen. 
- I read you, Charles. And I see you.

11
00:03:24,537 --> 00:03:27,415
<i>Well, eureka and all that. 
I found the bloody thing.</i>

12
00:03:28,875 --> 00:03:31,419
- What was that? 
- The <i>usual.</i>

13
00:03:31,586 --> 00:03:33,504
<i>This whole place does the shimmy.</i>

14
00:03:33,671 --> 00:03:36,507
<i>- How's the volcano? 
- Acting very much like</i> a <i>volcano...</i>

15
00:03:36,674 --> 00:03:38,343
<i>thank you very much.</i>

16
00:03:38,468 --> 00:03:41,596
<i>They tell me it's fine, 
but I wouldn't build condominiums.</i>

17
00:03:41,763 --> 00:03:43,973
Charles, did you really find it?

18
00:03:46,100 --> 00:03:49,312
<i>Chemically flawless, 
blue diamond alluvia.</i>

19
00:03:51,481 --> 00:03:54,275
<i>Johnny-on-the-spot phasic laser.</i>

20
00:03:54,442 --> 00:03:57,779
<i>This will look kind of raw 
without a real diamond.</i>

21
00:04:08,414 --> 00:04:10,875
<i>Would you say that test 
came back positive?</i>

22
00:04:11,042 --> 00:04:13,378
Oh, my God.

23
00:04:14,045 --> 00:04:18,216
<i>We found the sand in a mineral stream. 
Jeffrey's searching for the source.</i>

24
00:04:18,383 --> 00:04:22,720
<i>- I'll get Travis. 
- Wait. Jeffrey should share the glory.</i>

25
00:04:22,887 --> 00:04:25,932
<i>- Let's link up again in, uh, one hour. 
- Great.</i>

26
00:04:26,099 --> 00:04:28,268
- See you <i>in</i> an <i>hour.</i> 
- Give me your coordinates.

27
00:04:30,061 --> 00:04:31,938
Char...? Charles...?

28
00:04:36,609 --> 00:04:39,988
- Jeffrey. 
- Charlie, over here.

29
00:04:42,448 --> 00:04:46,244
Charlie, I think this 
may be really something.

30
00:04:46,411 --> 00:04:49,080
- We haven't got much time. 
<i>- I'll</i> show you.

31
00:04:51,124 --> 00:04:52,625
Jump in.

32
00:04:54,836 --> 00:04:57,005
- What? 
<i>- I'll</i> go first.

33
00:05:02,635 --> 00:05:04,137
I Jeffrey!

34
00:05:21,070 --> 00:05:22,405
I Jeffrey!

35
00:05:26,784 --> 00:05:29,370
- What is this? 
- Come on.

36
00:05:30,747 --> 00:05:35,168
From below it just looks like jungle, 
but it's not just jungle. See?

37
00:05:35,335 --> 00:05:37,253
Jesus Christ.

38
00:05:38,171 --> 00:05:42,508
This is a big deal. 
This is a big find.

39
00:05:42,675 --> 00:05:48,681
I can't believe it's just sitting here. 
All these centuries, waiting for lucky us.

40
00:05:53,728 --> 00:05:57,565
Listen, I raised Houston, 
they're getting the old man.

41
00:05:58,149 --> 00:06:00,610
Come on camera and share the glory.

42
00:06:00,777 --> 00:06:04,989
- We'll have to get another team here. 
- All right. Let me grab my bag.

43
00:06:16,834 --> 00:06:21,172
- Perfect, you say? A flawless diamond? 
- He found it. He was right.

44
00:06:21,339 --> 00:06:23,049
With the right laser and diamonds...

45
00:06:23,216 --> 00:06:25,885
we can dominate 
the communications industry over night.

46
00:06:26,052 --> 00:06:27,178
Has he found the source?

47
00:06:27,387 --> 00:06:31,557
Charles says a laser with a diamond 
like that can punch a hole in the moon.

48
00:06:31,724 --> 00:06:33,643
Shh. Don't say any more out here.

49
00:06:34,435 --> 00:06:35,978
- Where is he? 
- I don't know.

50
00:06:36,145 --> 00:06:39,148
- He should have transmitted 10 minutes ago. 
- Ugh.

51
00:06:39,315 --> 00:06:41,109
- Activate the remote. 
- Yes, sir.

52
00:06:47,949 --> 00:06:53,162
- I guess he's still looking for Jeffrey. 
- Hmm. Pan the camera.

53
00:07:00,753 --> 00:07:01,796
What in God's name...?

54
00:07:09,971 --> 00:07:13,433
Lock your remote. Back scan. 
Give me thermal readout.

55
00:07:17,728 --> 00:07:20,690
- I can see seven dead people. 
- What's that sound?

56
00:07:36,497 --> 00:07:39,709
- I didn't see him. Charles! 
- What?

57
00:07:41,335 --> 00:07:44,213
<i>- I'll</i> get help. 
- You can't get out. I had the code changed.

58
00:07:44,380 --> 00:07:46,591
Well, what is it?

59
00:07:47,133 --> 00:07:48,426
Rudy?

60
00:07:48,551 --> 00:07:51,012
- Sir? 
- Use the fire extinguisher on that.

61
00:07:57,393 --> 00:08:02,023
- No one knows this happened but us. 
- Families have to be be notified. Your wife.

62
00:08:02,190 --> 00:08:06,194
We don't know he's dead. 
If it's reported, they'll close the border.

63
00:08:06,319 --> 00:08:08,821
- What was that thing? 
- Uh, baboon.

64
00:08:08,988 --> 00:08:13,326
- I thought it was a gorilla, but I've never... 
- Gorillas didn't kill. Gorillas don't do that.

65
00:08:13,701 --> 00:08:17,622
- It could have been locals, a rival company. 
- Not another paranoid fantasy.

66
00:08:17,788 --> 00:08:20,082
I need those diamonds, Dr. Ross!

67
00:08:20,249 --> 00:08:22,543
- Are you for real? 
- It's the future.

68
00:08:22,710 --> 00:08:28,716
- Most believe children are the future. 
- 40,000 people, they all depend on me.

69
00:08:29,258 --> 00:08:31,719
This satellite is our cash cow.

70
00:08:31,886 --> 00:08:37,183
In three years it'll be obsolete. I need 
a new cash machine. This diamond's it!

71
00:08:37,350 --> 00:08:42,563
- Charles knew it. That's why he went. 
- He went into the Congo to please you.

72
00:08:42,730 --> 00:08:46,317
- I know you had feelings for him. 
- I almost married him.

73
00:08:46,484 --> 00:08:48,527
Listen to me, talking like he's...

74
00:08:48,694 --> 00:08:50,404
You have to go down there, Dr. Ross.

75
00:08:50,571 --> 00:08:53,908
You're good in the field. You were 
good in Panama. Once you're local...

76
00:08:54,033 --> 00:08:57,036
that laser's power pack 
should give off a readable signal.

77
00:08:57,161 --> 00:09:00,331
Find some expedition that's already going. 
Take it over.

78
00:09:00,498 --> 00:09:01,916
What are you talking about?

79
00:09:02,083 --> 00:09:05,962
There's no time! Once we let out what's 
happened, Zaire will shut the border.

80
00:09:06,128 --> 00:09:08,422
- By the time the investigation's... 
- Are you human?

81
00:09:08,589 --> 00:09:12,677
I'll be human later. Hire people 
when you get there. Good people.

82
00:09:12,843 --> 00:09:14,512
Never mind, I'll have some waiting.

83
00:09:14,887 --> 00:09:17,765
- Find out what happened to Charles. 
- Tell me you love your son.

84
00:09:17,932 --> 00:09:20,059
- I do. 
- And that's why you're sending me.

85
00:09:20,226 --> 00:09:22,144
It is.

86
00:09:22,311 --> 00:09:28,109
All right. But if I have one moment when 
I think otherwise, I'll make you sorry.

87
00:09:28,234 --> 00:09:29,819
That's a promise.

88
00:09:38,369 --> 00:09:40,579
<i>Oakland's number one classic station...</i>

89
00:09:40,746 --> 00:09:42,957
<i>taking you back in time, all the time.</i>

90
00:09:43,124 --> 00:09:45,042
<i>There's 
a crazy little shack</i>

91
00:09:45,209 --> 00:09:51,048
Wow. Isn't that beautiful? 
What's Amy's favorite color?

92
00:09:51,215 --> 00:09:57,179
Green, that's right. 
How green was my valley... Drop that!

93
00:09:57,346 --> 00:10:01,434
Good. Pretty. So pretty.

94
00:10:01,559 --> 00:10:06,856
No, Amy, on the paper. Yeah, okay, good.

95
00:10:07,023 --> 00:10:08,441
Amy, get some more paint.

96
00:10:11,068 --> 00:10:13,863
Good. That's green.

97
00:10:14,030 --> 00:10:17,825
No, Amy, on the paper. 
On... On the paper.

98
00:10:19,577 --> 00:10:23,039
Amy! Hey, you!

99
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:28,210
- How did she sleep? 
- Great night.

100
00:10:28,377 --> 00:10:30,171
- No nightmares? 
- Not a one.

101
00:10:30,338 --> 00:10:31,964
Good girl.

102
00:10:32,131 --> 00:10:33,966
That's my Amy.

103
00:10:35,009 --> 00:10:39,263
Richard, you better clean her up. 
It's showtime.

104
00:10:40,640 --> 00:10:42,892
When we started out, it was so simple.

105
00:10:43,059 --> 00:10:47,438
Communication is what separated 
human from animal. Speech.

106
00:10:48,230 --> 00:10:51,692
And for those humans who had 
am impairment that inhibited speech...

107
00:10:51,859 --> 00:10:54,528
sign language. An alphabet in gestures.

108
00:10:54,695 --> 00:10:58,074
Words in motion. Then came virtual reality.

109
00:10:58,240 --> 00:11:03,954
Sensors worn like clothing could read 
and replicate the body's movements.

110
00:11:04,372 --> 00:11:10,836
Arliss Wender at MIT was the first to 
apply this technology to sign language.

111
00:11:11,003 --> 00:11:15,883
<i>Our subject, William, 
was born without the organs of speech.</i>

112
00:11:16,050 --> 00:11:17,968
<i>Isn't that right, William?</i>

113
00:11:19,220 --> 00:11:23,182
<i>That is absolutely right.</i>

114
00:11:28,562 --> 00:11:34,193
<i>This is the first time 
I have ever heard my own voice.</i>

115
00:11:38,197 --> 00:11:42,702
Lights, please. 
It's hard to get grants for what I do.

116
00:11:43,077 --> 00:11:49,375
Most people just don't believe it. 
They think it's a parlor trick. A gag.

117
00:11:49,542 --> 00:11:51,669
But it's no gag, ladies and gentlemen.

118
00:11:51,836 --> 00:11:54,338
With this new technology, 
I can demonstrate it...

119
00:11:54,505 --> 00:11:58,592
in a way it has never been possible 
to demonstrate it before.

120
00:11:59,135 --> 00:12:00,803
Animals can talk.

121
00:12:02,054 --> 00:12:05,141
Amy, could you come down 
here please?

122
00:12:19,321 --> 00:12:22,825
Hello, Amy. Thank you for the flowers.

123
00:12:22,992 --> 00:12:25,369
<i>Peter. Hello, Peter.</i>

124
00:12:25,536 --> 00:12:26,829
Wow.

125
00:12:28,247 --> 00:12:32,001
Amy, how old are you?

126
00:12:32,168 --> 00:12:37,590
<i>Amy 7. Amy good gorilla.</i>

127
00:12:38,215 --> 00:12:40,217
<i>- Amy pretty. 
</i>

128
00:12:41,218 --> 00:12:43,429
Amy, look at me.

129
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:48,976
- Amy mother. 
- That's right. That's your baby.

130
00:12:49,143 --> 00:12:53,439
<i>- Amy wants lunch.</i> 
- Okay.

131
00:12:54,106 --> 00:12:59,028
- What do you think, Mrs. Romy? 
- It's spooky. Very spooky.

132
00:12:59,195 --> 00:13:04,200
Amy's above average intelligence 
for a gorilla, but she's not a freak.

133
00:13:04,784 --> 00:13:08,537
What she has learned, 
other gorillas have learned and can learn.

134
00:13:08,704 --> 00:13:11,499
But that takes money, of course. 
Isn't that right, Amy?

135
00:13:30,768 --> 00:13:32,895
Amy, calm down. Easy.

136
00:13:33,062 --> 00:13:36,357
Hey, hey, hey! Shh, shh. 
It's okay. You're all right.

137
00:13:38,317 --> 00:13:44,281
- You've got her sedated. She'll be fine. 
- She's not gonna be fine. Nightmares again.

138
00:13:44,406 --> 00:13:49,495
It's happened before. Gorillas in captivity 
degenerating mentally, having to be destroyed.

139
00:13:49,662 --> 00:13:53,040
When she did these paintings 
she got better. Why?

140
00:13:56,126 --> 00:14:01,840
Hey, hey... 
What's this room starting to look like?

141
00:14:04,009 --> 00:14:07,054
- The Jungle, she's been painting the jungle! 
- I don't know, Peter.

142
00:14:07,221 --> 00:14:08,347
She wants to go home.

143
00:14:08,514 --> 00:14:14,353
Peter, you did a great job. You taught a 
gorilla to talk, to paint, for gosh sakes.

144
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:18,440
When it comes to Amy, you can get a grant 
for anything except setting her free.

145
00:14:18,566 --> 00:14:21,235
How about this. I taught her, 
now she can teach them.

146
00:14:21,402 --> 00:14:22,987
- Who? 
- The mountain gorillas.

147
00:14:23,153 --> 00:14:26,282
We can translate 
what other animals are saying.

148
00:14:26,407 --> 00:14:29,535
Oh, please. Making you Dr. Doolittle?

149
00:14:29,702 --> 00:14:34,498
There isn't a foundation in motion that would 
fund an expedition with that objective.

150
00:14:34,665 --> 00:14:36,709
I will pay.

151
00:14:37,167 --> 00:14:41,463
- I will pay for Amy to go home. 
- And who are you?

152
00:14:42,172 --> 00:14:47,303
Herkermer Homolka. Formerly of Romania. 
Free now of the chains of Ceaucescu.

153
00:14:47,469 --> 00:14:50,681
Traveling the world, doing good.

154
00:14:53,892 --> 00:14:56,228
- A Romanian philanthropist? 
- Herkermer Homolka.

155
00:14:56,395 --> 00:14:59,189
- Something's voodoo. 
- Don't look a gift horse in the mouth.

156
00:14:59,356 --> 00:15:02,818
I don't think it's penetrating. 
We're taking Amy home. Get packed.

157
00:15:04,361 --> 00:15:08,741
Do you know where we're going? 
Amy, where are we going?

158
00:15:08,907 --> 00:15:12,536
- Jungle. <i>Me</i> jungle. 
- She's really excited.

159
00:15:12,703 --> 00:15:16,457
- Are you excited? 
- Me? I'm terrified.

160
00:15:16,624 --> 00:15:20,419
- Jungle. 
- Safari? I don't even like picnics. Nice glasses.

161
00:15:20,586 --> 00:15:22,713
<i>
Jungle. Me jungle.</i>

162
00:15:22,880 --> 00:15:27,301
<i>- That's right. Jungle. Home. 
- Tickle me. Tickle me.</i>

163
00:15:28,636 --> 00:15:30,429
Come on, time to go.

164
00:15:40,773 --> 00:15:42,524
Someone looking for me?

165
00:15:44,151 --> 00:15:48,447
Herkermer Homolka, hello. 
Uh, the transport.

166
00:15:48,614 --> 00:15:50,032
Oh, yeah. Um...

167
00:15:50,199 --> 00:15:53,911
- ls there a problem? 
- Not unless there's a problem.

168
00:15:59,625 --> 00:16:03,921
Are you excited, sweetheart? That's a 
camera. Be careful, it's expensive.

169
00:16:04,046 --> 00:16:07,049
I think she's got a real eye.

170
00:16:07,216 --> 00:16:11,929
- Karen Ross. Professor Karen Ross. 
- Professor Peter Elliot.

171
00:16:12,096 --> 00:16:13,472
- Doctor. 
- Doctor.

172
00:16:13,639 --> 00:16:16,266
Have you got my faxes, 
Fed Exes and phone calls?

173
00:16:16,433 --> 00:16:18,560
- I'm sorry, you're the one. 
- Yes, I'm the one.

174
00:16:18,686 --> 00:16:20,729
We've put together a hasty expedition.

175
00:16:20,896 --> 00:16:23,065
To the Congo, with a talking gorilla.

176
00:16:23,232 --> 00:16:27,111
- Jungle me. Jungle. <i>Tickle</i> Amy. 
- That's right, jungle. Just a minute, Amy.

177
00:16:27,277 --> 00:16:30,989
- I'm sorry... I'm afraid that's impossible. 
- I need to join up with you.

178
00:16:31,156 --> 00:16:32,616
- Excuse me. 
- Yeah?

179
00:16:32,783 --> 00:16:35,953
- I have all the visas. 
- Go ahead and load this stuff on the plane.

180
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:38,622
- We're taking this stuff off the plane. 
- Off the plane?

181
00:16:38,789 --> 00:16:42,292
- I can pay part of the cost. 
- Why take stuff off the plane?

182
00:16:42,459 --> 00:16:46,588
- I'm sorry, we don't need any money. 
- You're flying way under capacity.

183
00:16:46,755 --> 00:16:48,298
You can easily find room for me.

184
00:16:48,465 --> 00:16:52,177
- It's not a matter of that. It's Amy. 
<i>- Ugly</i> woman.

185
00:16:52,344 --> 00:16:54,555
- The gorilla? 
- She gets jealous very easily.

186
00:16:54,722 --> 00:16:57,057
Somebody tell me 
why you're unloading the plane.

187
00:16:57,224 --> 00:16:59,727
- Talk to the operations guy. 
- Can't you tell me?

188
00:16:59,893 --> 00:17:01,895
- No. 
- I've gotta get on this plane.

189
00:17:02,062 --> 00:17:06,108
I've got to be listed with your manifest, 
or my visas are worthless. Name your price.

190
00:17:06,275 --> 00:17:09,403
I don't have a price. I'm not a pound 
of sugar, I'm a primatologist.

191
00:17:09,570 --> 00:17:12,072
Don't be hasty, Dr. Elliot.

192
00:17:12,906 --> 00:17:15,659
Herkermer Homolka, 
formerly of Romania.

193
00:17:15,826 --> 00:17:18,620
- Dr. Karen Ross. 
- There seems to be some glitch.

194
00:17:18,787 --> 00:17:21,540
- They're unloading the plane. 
- Yes.

195
00:17:22,875 --> 00:17:27,296
Unfortunately there has been 
a slight interruption in my credit flow.

196
00:17:27,463 --> 00:17:31,091
- I am unable to pay for the fuel. 
- I'll pay for the fuel.

197
00:17:31,258 --> 00:17:35,679
<i>- I'll</i> pay for it. How much is the fuel? 
- Fifty-six thousand dollars.

198
00:17:35,804 --> 00:17:37,181
Fifty-six thousand?

199
00:17:38,766 --> 00:17:40,350
What are you smiling about?

200
00:17:40,517 --> 00:17:42,728
You need me, Dr. Elliot.

201
00:17:49,193 --> 00:17:51,862
<i>Taxi to</i> 
runway, three-one <i>left.</i>

202
00:17:52,780 --> 00:17:54,448
<i>This is your captain speaking.</i>

203
00:17:54,615 --> 00:17:56,658
<i>- Hey. 
- We've been cleared for take-off.</i>

204
00:17:56,825 --> 00:18:00,704
<i>Please make sure that your seat belts 
are fastened and that all carry-on...</i>

205
00:18:00,871 --> 00:18:04,458
We're returning her to the jungle 
from whence she came.

206
00:18:04,625 --> 00:18:06,627
From the look of it, not a moment too soon.

207
00:18:07,544 --> 00:18:11,632
That's it. Good girl. Here's an egg.

208
00:18:12,966 --> 00:18:13,967
Unh.

209
00:18:14,134 --> 00:18:17,304
We do not throw things. 
- ls that animal dangerous?

210
00:18:17,846 --> 00:18:20,474
Humans are dangerous, 
gorillas are very gentle.

211
00:18:25,854 --> 00:18:27,064
It's okay, Amy.

212
00:18:27,231 --> 00:18:29,650
<i>Where ground?</i>

213
00:18:29,817 --> 00:18:31,985
- Where ground? 
- It's fine. We're flying.

214
00:18:32,152 --> 00:18:37,282
- We're going to the jungle. 
- Amy want <i>green</i> drop <i>drink.</i>

215
00:18:37,449 --> 00:18:41,912
<i>- No. 
- Amy want green drop drink.</i>

216
00:18:42,079 --> 00:18:43,580
All right, all right.

217
00:18:45,040 --> 00:18:47,584
You'd swear they were married.

218
00:18:47,751 --> 00:18:53,715
The notion of the "killer ape" may be politically 
incorrect, but that's not to say it's untrue.

219
00:18:53,882 --> 00:18:55,592
I can't believe what I'm hearing.

220
00:18:57,344 --> 00:19:00,430
Cliches usually contain some 
element of truth.

221
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:11,149
- Are you serving that ape a martini? 
- She's allowed one. It'll calm her down.

